# Persistence Principles

Use this rule when designing or modifying persistence behavior.

## Core Rule

Persistence must support correctness, traceability, and operational support.

This system is not storing only business data. It is also storing session lifecycle, set history, and user progress.

## Persistence Priorities

Persist data in a way that preserves:

- current state (user, active/completed session, sets, set groups)
- meaningful history (sessions over time, progress queries)
- supportability after failure (no silent data loss, understandable schema)
- data integrity (no overwrite of confirmed data by unconfirmed or conflicting data)

## Prefer

Prefer:

- explicit persistence models (users, sessions, sets, set_groups or equivalent)
- clear distinction between current session state and historical records
- intentional repository boundaries
- schema shapes that support operations (history, progress), not just happy-path reads

## Avoid

Avoid:

- overwriting meaningful history carelessly
- mixing unrelated lifecycle concerns into one opaque record
- persistence shortcuts that destroy supportability (e.g. persisting unconfirmed sets when the rule is to confirm first)
- schema changes with unclear operational effect

## Business Rule Alignment

Do not persist:

- incomplete sets (e.g. missing reps or weight) without explicit confirmation having been recorded
- conflicting set data without clarification
- sets that the voice pipeline classified as unrecognized or ambiguous without user confirmation

Persistence layer should receive already-validated, confirmed structures from the application layer.

## Final Rule

If persistence makes it hard to reconstruct what happened to a session or set (when it was stored, whether it was confirmed), the design is too weak.
